STREPTOCOCCUS GROUP A, SCARLET FEVER - CHINA (11): (HONG KONG, MACAU)
REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
*********************************************************************************************

A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 13 Jul 2011
From: Barry Dyer <barry.dyer@internationalsos.com> [edited]


Following the reports of scarlet fever in Mainland China and an
earlier brief request for information on the magnitude of the outbreak
there this year [see ProMED-mail Streptococcus group A, scarlet fever
- China (02): (HK,MO) 20110623.1918], the Ministry of Health
epidemiological data have been published and are available [in
Chinese] at
http://www.moh.gov.cn/publicfiles/business/htmlfiles/mohjbyfkzj/s3578/201107/52298.htm
and
http://www.moh.gov.cn/publicfiles/business/htmlfiles/mohjbyfkzj/s3578/201106/52004.htm.

A machine translation of the National Notifiable Infectious Diseases
table reveals:
Scarlet fever cases reported in June 2011: 9773
May 2011: 9308
April 2011: 5023
March 2011: 2795
February 2011: 1000
January 2011: 3100
Total year to date (YTD): 30 999

With the report from the Centre for Health Protection in Hong Kong as
of 13 Jul 2011
(http://res.chp.gov.hk/seb/files/scarlet_fever_daily_update.pdf):
874 cases YTD, more than 200 cases in the past 2 weeks alone; this
outbreak does not appear to be showing any signs of slowing any time
soon.

--
Dr Barry Dyer
Manager, Medical Information and Analysis
International SOS UK Ltd.
<barry.dyer@internationalsos.com>

[The data above are number of scarlet fever cases reported monthly
for Mainland China, excluding Hong Kong and Taiwan. For Mainland China
with 30 999 cases and a population of over 1.3 billion
(http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Demographics_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China),
the incidence rate for the 1st half of 2011 is 2.4 per 100 000.
However, the incidence rate of scarlet fever in 2011 for Guangdong,
the Mainland China province that surrounds Hong Kong, would be helpful
for comparison with current Hong Kong data. For Hong Kong the
incidence rate for the 1st half of 2011 is 12.5 per 100 000. For
comparison, the annual incidence rates of scarlet fever reported for
Hong Kong in the past decade has been 2 to 3 per 100 000
(<http://www.gideononline.com/tag/scarlet-fever/), and for England
and Wales in the years 1999-2009 about 4 per 100 000
(http://www.hpa.org.uk/web/HPAwebFile/HPAweb_C/1251473364307).

Genotypic characterization of outbreak isolates by molecular methods
such as multilocus sequence typing, ribotyping, pulsed-field gel
electrophoresis (PFGE), and random amplified polymorphic DNA (RAPD)
analysis of the isolates will aid identifying common outbreak strains.
We await this information.

Incidence rates of scarlet fever in 2011 for Guangdong, the Mainland
China province that surrounds Hong Kong and incidence rates in 2010
would be helpful for comparison with current Hong Kong data.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Hong Kong and neighboring
China and Macau can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/0_xc.
Mod.ML]
